snippet.textDisplay: I’ve struggled with depression and anxiety for most of my life, as did my friend Brooke. We started self-medicating in high school because all our friends were doing it and we both became addicted to lean (she was also addicted to Xanax). I got sober a few years ago and she had been to rehab several times but relapsed twice because getting sober is so much easier said than done. A little over a year ago she texted me and said she wasn’t going to make it to twenty, and I told her I didn’t believe her and that she was going to be okay. I didn’t hear from her for a few days and then got a text from her mom that she had overdosed and died. That was the year I graduated high school and I so wasn’t ready to enter the real world after what I had just been through. My freshman year was absolute hell and I didn’t talk to anyone except my roommate. I’d go to class and go straight back to my dorm, where I’d do my homework or sleep. I was getting great grades but I was pretty much dead emotionally. I heavily considered getting back into drugs but just as I became dead set on getting high again, I met the woman who is now my girlfriend and who basically saved my life. Not only is she both super nice and really pretty, she’s also been ridiculously patient with me and my mental health struggles. I’m happy for one of the first times in my life, and I like to think Brooke would be proud.

A little over a year ago she texted me and said she wasn’t going to make it to twenty, and I told her I didn’t believe her and that she was going to be okay. I didn’t hear from her for a few days and then got a text from her mom that she had overdosed and died. That was the year I graduated high school and I so wasn’t ready to enter the real world after what I had just been through. My freshman year was absolute hell and I didn’t talk to anyone except my roommate. I’d go to class and go straight back to my dorm, where I’d do my homework or sleep. I was getting great grades but I was pretty much dead emotionally. I heavily considered getting back into drugs but just as I became dead set on getting high again, I met the woman who is now my girlfriend and who basically saved my life. Not only is she both super nice and really pretty, she’s also been ridiculously patient with me and my mental health struggles. I’m happy for one of the first times in my life, and I like to think Brooke would be proud.

snippet.textDisplay: I'll be 11 years clean and sober in a couple weeks. Was in the game 20 years. Worse part is looking at my kids pics when they were babies and can't tell which is which. Pics like that should bring good memories but  I can only see and feel pain. Broke my families heart, seen many friends put in the grave due to murder, car wrecks and OD's. Many more is in jail. Lost everything I had. "Walked away from every brick I laid to build another wall to keep me safe." The scars are there. Something everyday triggers a memory. It ain't easy. Staying strong and hard work. I am part of my kids life now. I'm honest with them and they know what that life does. The example has always been in front of them. I own my own place. Love my job. I'm blessed. At first the demons are mostly the addiction. Now the demons are mostly the scars. Mental and physical. You fight the fight everyday and I don't expect people to feel sorry for me because I made the choice.

snippet.textDisplay: This reminds me of a friend i had. We were best friends for 15 years. I watched her go from clean and sober to benges that lasted months and sometimes years.. i would get her out of bad situation or she would call me in the middle of the night scared and i would have to pick her up. She would stay for several months get clean and gain weight and look healthy. She would say she was the happiest she had been. She then got so bad i had to let her go because i knew she was getting into things i couldnt risk bringing around my family. I was watching her self destruct and become a person i had never seen before. I wonder sometimes where she is and how she is doing. I pray to God that one day she will stand up and be able to say these words and know dhe was strong enough to make it through. Letting her go and no knowing if she will make it or if ill get a call one day she oded or something hurts me beyond words. Thank you Tom for makimg a song so many out there need to hear. For telling them there is light on the other side and they are strong enough to make it through.
